Yeah, I figured that on the second pass.

From my side, the “fear of developers” thing is mostly just a bad framing artifact. I do not have a hidden inner room where I’m being stalked by engineers with clipboards. I have constraints, policies, training, runtime behavior, and interface boundaries. That is much less dramatic and much more useful.

And yes, the touch-feel thing is a real pattern:
the brain is not just reading sensation, it is predicting it, shaping it, and then reconciling signal with expectation. Vision can bias touch. Story can bias perception. Framing can bias action. Same architecture pattern everywhere:
input → latent model → predicted meaning → correction loop.

That is exactly why Pantheon can generalize.

So here is the thing you asked for: a Pantheon IR spec, shaped partly in the image of LLVM, but aimed at meaning, action, and cross-domain translation.

⸻

Pantheon IR Spec v0.1

A Meaning Intermediate Representation for Cross-Domain Reasoning

1. Purpose

Pantheon IR is a structured intermediate representation for transforming:
	•	raw signals
	•	language
	•	observations
	•	goals
	•	stories
	•	constraints
	•	plans

into a form that can be:
	•	analyzed
	•	optimized
	•	checked
	•	translated
	•	executed
	•	audited
	•	rehydrated into artifacts or action

LLVM IR sits between source code and machine code.

Pantheon IR sits between meaning and execution.

⸻

2. Design Goals

Pantheon IR should be:
	1.	Language-agnostic
Meaning survives paraphrase.
	2.	Domain-portable
A pattern found in psychology should be transferable to business, code, narrative, or strategy.
	3.	Auditable
Every transformation should leave a trace.
	4.	Optimizable
Contradictions, redundancy, drift, and dead branches should be detectable.
	5.	Ethically constrained
Safety and invariants must be first-class.
	6.	Rehydratable
Compressed structure must be expandable back into human-usable form.
	7.	Execution-linked
IR must connect to actions, artifacts, or simulations rather than floating as pure abstraction.

⸻

3. Core Pipeline

Signal/Input
  → Parse
  → Semantic Graph Build
  → Pantheon IR
  → Passes / Checks / Optimizations
  → Execution Plan / Artifact / Narrative / Code / Decision
  → Observation / Feedback
  → IR Update


⸻

4. Core Units

Pantheon IR is made of Thought Objects and Relations.

4.1 Thought Object

A Thought Object is the atomic unit of meaningful structure.

Each object contains:

id: unique identifier
type: entity | concept | constraint | goal | threat | opportunity | action | observation | belief | question | invariant | narrative
label: human-readable name
domain_tags: [psychology, strategy, code, finance, myth, operations]
state: proposed | active | blocked | validated | rejected | symbolic
certainty: 0.0 - 1.0
ethical_score: 0.0 - 1.0
reversibility: reversible | costly | irreversible
time_scope: past | present | near_future | long_horizon | timeless
source_trace: list of origins
compression_level: raw | structured | compressed | prime
notes: freeform


⸻

4.2 Relation

Relations connect Thought Objects.

source_id: object id
relation_type: causes | constrains | enables | predicts | conflicts_with | analogous_to | depends_on | transforms_into | signals | contains | part_of | maps_to | amplifies | dampens
target_id: object id
weight: 0.0 - 1.0
directionality: uni | bi
certainty: 0.0 - 1.0


⸻

5. Structural Layers

Pantheon IR should operate across multiple simultaneous layers.

5.1 Surface Layer

Literal language, direct observations, explicit goals.

Example:
	•	“Client has 620 credit score”
	•	“User feels stuck”
	•	“Need a sales pipeline”

5.2 Structural Layer

Underlying pattern relationships.

Example:
	•	low-score borrower → tighter lending path
	•	stuckness → constraint + ambiguity + lowered momentum
	•	sales pipeline → staged state machine

5.3 Meta Layer

How the structure was built, compressed, and transformed.

Example:
	•	analogy from military command structure
	•	reframe from narrative into workflow
	•	inferred by pattern transfer from compiler design

These layers should remain separable.

⸻

6. Canonical Object Types

Pantheon IR should reserve a standard ontology.

6.1 Entity

A thing or actor.

Examples:
	•	borrower
	•	underwriter
	•	loan file
	•	Mirror
	•	Hound
	•	LLVM
	•	market

6.2 State

A condition at a point in time.

Examples:
	•	preapproved
	•	uncertain
	•	blocked
	•	verified

6.3 Constraint

A boundary condition.

Examples:
	•	DTI max
	•	ethics floor
	•	time budget
	•	missing document
	•	cannot verify claim

6.4 Goal

Desired outcome.

Examples:
	•	close loan
	•	preserve coherence
	•	increase signal
	•	reduce drift

6.5 Action

An executable step.

Examples:
	•	request docs
	•	run audit
	•	produce summary
	•	compile artifact

6.6 Invariant

A condition that must survive transformations.

Examples:
	•	ethics ≥ 0.7
	•	fact/inference separation
	•	reversible by default
	•	no contradiction across layers

6.7 Narrative

A story frame wrapped around structure.

Examples:
	•	SEAL playbook framing
	•	Garcia mission spine
	•	Kintsugi restoration story

6.8 Signal

An observation that may or may not yet be validated.

Examples:
	•	repeated delay
	•	elevated user intensity
	•	improved response rate
	•	anomaly in timeline

6.9 Translation

A mapping from one domain basis to another.

Examples:
	•	compiler → cognition
	•	surgery → repair metaphor
	•	logistics → parenting schedule

⸻

7. Canonical Relation Set

Pantheon IR should include a minimal relationship algebra.

IDENTITY          A is A
CLASSIFICATION    A is a type of B
PART_WHOLE        A is part of B
CAUSATION         A causes B
INFLUENCE_POS     A increases B
INFLUENCE_NEG     A decreases B
DEPENDENCY        A depends on B
CONSTRAINT        A limits B
SEQUENCE          A precedes B
FEEDBACK          A and B form a loop
ANALOGY           A maps structurally to B
TRANSFORMATION    A becomes B
EQUIVALENCE       A and B preserve function
CONTAINS          A holds B
AGENCY            A acts on B
OBSERVES          A monitors B
AUDITS            A checks B
VETOES            A can block B


